While I was sick and not checking the internet, serious changes: Ghalibaf dropped out and supported Raisi. I didn't think this would happen because it doesn't make sense to reduce Raisi's long term legitimacy on what I perceived to be a long shot to get Raisi to win this, as it would deteriorate his ability to eventually go for supreme leader, but now that it's happened, I'm starting to consider the possibility that this might be because the establishment knows that Raisi's going to win, e.g., rigging the election. I still think that's unlikely in the broad scheme of things, because of what happened in 2009 when similar things were alleged, and the Arab Spring probably convinced hardliners that a big popular uprising isn't great even though the Iranians are probably better coup-proofed, but it still could happen. As such, I'm going to adjust up and down after adding Ghalibaf's former percentage to Raisi. This is very worrying. That being said, I still think that Rohani's going to take it. I don't see voter turnout dropping that much, nor do I see Raisi gaining all of the conservative faction. But this is still cause for worry.

Looks very good for Rohani, but stay tuned just in case.

Even with two ascendant opponents, Rouhani remains a force to be reckoned with. Precedent and privilege favors the incumbent; no sitting president in the Islamic Republic has ever lost his bid for reelection—at least, not in terms of the official vote tally. And Rouhani can claim a record of some genuine achievement over the past four years: first and foremost as an architect of the nuclear deal, which the majority of Iranians celebrated, but also in restoring Iran’s place in the world, reviving ties with traditional trade partners, taming hyperinflation, and generating strong GDP growth.
AP report today that Ghalibaf has dropped out to allow Raisa a straight run as prefered candidate of the religious right.

Rohani has never dipped below 50% in the polls, and unless one drops out, his foes will split the remaining difference.

http://ippogroup.com/ http://www.iranpolitik.com/2017/05/13/iran-election-watch/rouhani-fires-leading-rival-week-iran-election/ Rouhani, I think, will still take it handily. Scattered reports suggest that the Rouhani's success depends on turnout, and that turnout is in danger. I think that's stretching it. [http://www.belfercenter.org/sites/default/files/legacy/files/Iran%20Elections%20-%20web.pdf] If we look at last year's parliamentary elections, in which the moderates did quite well, turnout was 2% higher than normal. Also, in places like Tehran where turnout was roughly 50%, the Republicans (Iranian moderates) did extraordinarily well, winning every seat up for grabs. A couple things that could tip the scales: the Ayotollah coming in hard for a candidate. The candidate he's most likely to do so for, if he did, would be Ebrahim Raisi, as they reportedly are quite similar in viewpoints. But the issue here is that if Ebrahim Raisi lost anyways, which TBH is likely, even if Ghalibaf drops out and favors him, the Ayotollah would be embarassed, and because Raisi is reportedly his preferred successor, he would also de-legitimatize him. I think it's too risky. Another thing that might harm his chances is that if in the upcoming visit to Riyadh by Prez. Trump, something particularly hawkish is said/planned. If the relations are too antagonistic, this could push the electorate to the right. But especially because of the dangers of doing so, I think that Gen. McMaster and SecDef Mattis will be strongly cautioning against this. A strong statement against Iran could be intended to direct attention away from the Comey hubbub, but in the broad scheme of things, I doubt that anything too antagonistic will be said considering that Trump isn't really planning on doing any big speeches right now.
If Rouhani doesn't hit 50% in the first round, there will be a runoff; this seems probable. He'll likely win that, but I'm coming down a little bit to indicate minimal nervousness about that outcome.

Bit of guess work as there don't seem to be any great domestic polls. From the "Iranpolls" data it looks like a fairly large proportion (56%) of Iranian's think Rohani might lose though, so I think many of the probabilities below might be overstating it. I've taken the results of this survey and adjusted it (roughly) for incumbency bias. Rohani appears to remain popular according to available polling, but so do his challengers. And most people seem to think the domestic situation has deteriorated.
All my political predictions are based on the charisma/persuasion heuristic. Proposed by Paul Graham here: http://www.paulgraham.com/charisma.html

While Raisi is popular, he is there to secure support for the technocracy and will stand aside in favour of Rohani if needed. This moves Rohani likely chance of wining much higher than his current polls. It also leaves Ghalibaf as the only real alternative to the incumbent.

1) Starting roughly with the last poll numbers. Rouhani is polling at double the next closest candidate. ( https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Opinion_polling_for_the_Iranian_presidential_election,_2017#Pre-2017_polls )

I have based my forecast based on two main questions (and all the scenarios that could come about) : What are the chances that this election would go to a second round? If it does, who would be the two participants and who would come on top?

Have to agree with other forecasters that Rouhani is looking like the popular candidate and Ghalibaf is his main rival. Eshaq Jahangiri is emerging as favourite of reformists, though he entered the race to help Rouhani. “Jahangiri has tried to portray Ghalibaf as a continuation of Ahmadinejad, condemning his military mindset” (https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/may/04/shadow-candidate-in-iranian-election-overshadows-rouhani). Jahangiri is also a close ally of Mohammad Khatami who has publicly endorsed Rouhani for this years elections.

https://www.foreignaffairs.com/articles/iran/2017-04-28/rouhani-s-path-second-term?cid=nlc-fatoday-20170505&sp_mid=54000758&sp_rid=bml0aXNoLnZhaWR5YW5hdGhhbkBnbWFpbC5jb20S1&spMailingID=54000758&spUserID=MjEwNDg3MDc5NzYxS0&spJobID=1160843145&spReportId=MTE2MDg0MzE0NQS2 Based on this article, and a few others I've read in other places that I can't remember, I'd say Rohani's looking like the obvious favorite. Looking at the previous election results (which is probably the best predictor of this one), Rohani wiped the floor with Ghalibaf. Ebrahim Raisi, aside from potentially being the favorite of the Ayotollah, doesn't have a whole lot of other things going for him. Look at the amount of people that don't know him in the poll [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Opinion_polling_for_the_Iranian_presidential_election,_2017] The FA article suggests that Rohani has gotten an increasing amount of support across the political spectrum. He won handily in 2013, and especially with the huge leap in Iranian economic growth, and with the courting of conservative factions, I think it would take a miracle, or some shady business, for Ghalibaf to come close. This is a more cautious estimate than some of the others for a few reasons: I think that the Raisi camp is going to fold and go for Ghalibaf sometime soon. While Raisi is reportedly more favorable with the Supreme Leader, as mentioned earlier, nobody knows who he is. While I still think that Ghalibaf has meager chances, in part due to the fact that many Iranians surely associated recent successes with Rohani, that boost could be useful. I do not think, as some have suggested, that Ghalibaf will drop in favor of Raisi. He has been gaining steam lately, but I simply doubt he can gain enough steam to paint himself as a credible alternative to Ghalibaf within a few weeks. If that changes, I'll update. What worries me about my forecast (and I daresay personally worries me) is some kind of aggressive statement by the Trump administration could bolster support for hardliners. If it went poorly, it could very well boost Raisi's support enough to attract Ghalibaf's votes, and start to push more moderate conservatives to Raisi's side as well. I think the Administration knows this, so they will probably be careful, but a stray tweet could lead to a large percentage change in my estimates. That being said, I ultimately still see Rohani winning this. http://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-22916174 Also, https://www.brookings.edu/blog/markaz/2017/05/03/who-will-rule-iran-tehrans-presidential-election-foreshadows-succession-politics/?utm_campaign=Foreign%20Policy&utm_source=hs_email&utm_medium=email&utm_content=51590492 Ghalibaf is still the conservative candidate to beat. And as the article notes, it's simply too risky to try and do any kind of large scale rigging when Rohani's doing just fine.

There are not many polls or at least reliable ones. The general view towards this election seems to be that of pessimism and general outlook towards the economy is not good. People have a less favourable opinion on Iran Deal Rouhani's main achievement.
TV censors Rouhani documentary ahead of elections

The conservatives will only field a single candidate in the election. That will likely be the most popular one. So only Rohani and Ghalibaf are likely to compete in the actual election. Jahangiri is also only there to support Rohani. So there are only 2 actual candidates.

The tension between the new US administration and Iran might play into the hardliners hands. Mr Raisi said "Why have you [Rouhani] kept the country idle for four years waiting for others to open the knots?". Thousands of his supporters responded by chanting "death to the US" (https://www.ft.com/content/fdfedfa6-2e79-11e7-9555-23ef563ecf9a).

Rohani - steady hand, centrist, quasi-reformist with good rep and cred with the regime. Big changes coming if the Supreme Leader passes away. Country and Elites don't want someone to rock the boat, especially with the number of conflicts erupting and escalating in Syria and Yemen as well as the incoming ground swell from European trade.

I am sure Rohani wins for two reasons, polling and tradition. The handful of polls I have found show the incumbent well ahead of any of his rivals, hovering around 50%. Although on that subject, I have had a lot of trouble finding polls for the election, does anyone know a good source? Second, I know this is a small sample size but since the Islamic revolution there have been four other presidents and no one has yet lost his reelection bid. I don't think Rohani will be any different. Particularly because, after a rough 2015, the economy is growing again.
He got Iran a sweet deal and people will repay him.
The standing of the sitting president is strong, and the spread of the other candidates make it highly improbable that any of them will make the election
